    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Japan's Apology</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman Ryuichiro Yamazaki disputes August 7 article, which asserted that Japan has never fully apologized to China for actions during World War II</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Miffed Chinese Sue Japan Companies'' (news article, Aug. 7):</p>
        <p>The article asserts that Japan has never fully apologized to China for Japan's actions during World War II. But Japan has repeatedly stated its apology for its wartime actions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Miffed Chinese Sue Japan Companies'' (news article, Aug. 7):</p>
        <p>The article asserts that Japan has never fully apologized to China for Japan's actions during World War II. But Japan has repeatedly stated its apology for its wartime actions.</p>
        <p>A notable example is the official statement in August 1995 in which Tomiichi Murayama, then the prime minister, said that Japan ''through its colonial rule and aggression, caused tremendous damage and suffering to the people of many countries, particularly to those of Asian nations.'' Mr. Murayama expressed his ''feelings of deep remorse'' and ''heartfelt apology.''</p>
        <p>As recently as 1998, Keizo Obuchi, then prime minister, reiterated the gist of this statement to President Jiang Zemin of China when he paid a state visit to Japan.</p>
        <p>RYUICHIRO YAMAZAKI  Spokesman  Ministry of Foreign Affairs  Tokyo, Aug. 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
